Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.00,0:00:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1784, William Hollins starts a business in Pleasley, Derbyshire.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.00,0:00:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The business creates a fabric called Viyella.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:14.80,0:00:19.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Viyella is a signature Irish fabric loved by people around the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.00,0:00:23.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Viyella is registered as a trademark in 1894,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.75,0:00:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and in 1907, the trademark is registered in the US of A.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:28.50,0:00:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Woohoo!
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.50,0:00:30.75,Default,,0,0,0,,But in the sixties,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.00,0:00:37.00,Default,,0,0,0,,many poor young girls who are kept in places called Magdalene asylums are made to work for Viyella.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.10,0:00:40.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Magdalene asylums were places where girls could be put
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.60,0:00:44.00,Default,,0,0,0,,when they had a baby and the baby's father ran away.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.25,0:00:47.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Some of the girls got pregnant because they were raped.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.35,0:00:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Then they were put in a Magdalene asylum,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.10,0:00:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,so the church could put their life back in order.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.50,0:00:56.20,Default,,0,0,0,,While they were staying in the Magdalene asylums,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.30,0:00:58.50,Default,,0,0,0,,the girls had a lot of work to do.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.75,0:01:00.90,Default,,0,0,0,,They were washing clothes in the laundries,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.00,0:01:03.50,Default,,0,0,0,,and they were making Viyella fabric too.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.80,0:01:06.50,Default,,0,0,0,,The church got money for the Viyella fabric,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.60,0:01:10.75,Default,,0,0,0,,but the church did not pay the girls any money for making the fabric.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:11.00,0:01:14.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Both the church and the Viyella business made good money.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.60,0:01:17.75,Default,,0,0,0,,The poor little penitents kept working and working,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.85,0:01:21.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and many of them stayed in the asylums for a long, long time.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.00,0:01:27.50,Default,,0,0,0,,In 2010, the Irish Human Rights Commission told the government that the penitents,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.60,0:01:28.75,Default,,0,0,0,,who are now old,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.85,0:01:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,should finally get some money
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.10,0:01:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,for all the work that they did when they were young girls.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.10,0:01:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But the government did not do anything.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.10,0:01:36.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyhoo.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.00,0:01:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In 2024, Morrison McConnell celebrate 240 years of Viyella.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.50,0:01:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Viyella is a Morrison McConnell brand,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:46.20,0:01:48.80,Default,,0,0,0,,and Morrison McConnell will continue to give people
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.90,0:01:51.25,Default,,0,0,0,,the Viyella fabric that they love.
